Hi @WilkAndy, thank you for the prompt and detailed replies! Below are some comments on your points:

I understand a bit better the principles of the PorousFlowPeacemanBorehole, especially this element-size dependency. I have run a model with smaller elements and I saw that the pressure is decreasing earlier than compared with larger elements;
Thanks for the hint, I have tried an isothermal case and the changes in pressure compared to cold injection are very small (but non exactly 0, see the plot). Concerning mobility, I have tried a case with constant relative permeability but it does not converge. Perhaps it is because of null capillary force (my guess is that constant pc and rel_perm make it difficult for the PS formulation to calculate sgas);
Capillarity is null because I fixed capillary pressure pc=0 on purpose, I wanted to isolate the effects for now. But your hint is correct, I have tried with the capillary pressure and the results show that indeed higher retention properties (VanGenuchten with alpha=8e-7 and m=0.6) keep the gas pressure closer to the prescribed values from the PorousFlowPeacemanBorehole. One question: is there a way to make the retention properties temperature-dependent? For example, through temperature-dependent surface tension?
I have another question on the usage of PorousFlowPeacemanBorehole in a true 2D setting. I have run an example of that but I do not fully understand what would be the meaning of the out-of-plane size of the wellbore? A 2D model is usually assumed as unit thickness in the out-of-plane direction, so what would be for example a PorousFlowPeacemanBorehole with 2 points, one of which with a z coordinate (assuming 2D is in x,y) is 100 m? I have run some tests and observed that the injected mass flow rate reaches an asymptotic limit with the increasing out-of-plane size of the PorousFlowPeacemanBorehole. I have tried different sizes from 1m to 3000m and found that at approximately 500m out-of-plane well length, the mass flow rate was 99.2% the one of 3000m wellbore size. I am not sure about its physical interpretation, or if it is even correct to use PorousFlowPeacemanBorehole in a 2D case.

The figure below shows the results of the different trials. The light grey plots indicate the base case, for comparison.

I want to write the computeResidual() function in Kernel.C in a way that is suitable for multiple variables, where p is the pth variable, and I want to know if _re_blocks is designed for multiple variables, if the number of rows or columns of the residual matrix is affected by the number of variables, and to accommodate multiple variables, " MooseIndex(_vector_tags) i = 0; i < _vector_tags.size(); i++, ++vector_tag" how to rewrite the loop statement?
for (unsigned int p = 0; p < _n_equation; ++p)
	{
		  _re_blocks.resize(_vector_tags.size());
		  mooseAssert(_vector_tags.size() >= 1, "we need at least one active tag");
		  auto vector_tag = _vector_tags.begin();
		  for (MooseIndex(_vector_tags) i = 0; i < _vector_tags.size(); i++, ++vector_tag)
		    _re_blocks[i] = &assembly.residualBlock(p, *vector_tag);
		  _local_re.resize(_re_blocks[0]->size());

		for (_qp = 0; _qp < _qrule->n_points(); _qp++)
		{
			precalculateResidual();
			for (_i = 0; _i < _test.size(); _i++)
				_local_re(_i)+=_JxW[_qp] * _coord[_qp] * computeQpResidual(p);
		}

	  for (auto & re : _re_blocks)
	    *re += _local_re;
	}
